# 4. Split the date variable into month, day, and year variables. In which month is the highest average volume of avocado sales?
avocados["date"] = pd.to_datetime(avocados["date"])
avocados["year"] = avocados["date"].dt.year
avocados["month"] = avocados["date"].dt.month
avocados["day"] = avocados["date"].dt.day
avocados.columns
Index(['date', 'average_price', 'total_volume', 'small_avocados',
       'large_avocados', 'xl_avocados', 'total_bags', 'small_bags',
       'large_bags', 'xlarge_bags', 'type', 'year', 'geography', 'geo_type',
       'month', 'day'],
      dtype='object')
avg_monthly_volume = (avocados
                      .groupby("month")["total_volume"]
                      .mean()
                      .sort_values(ascending=False))
avg_monthly_volume

# 7. In which California regions is the price of organic versus conventional avocados most different?
# Support your answer with a few summary statistics AND a visualization.
price_summary = (
    avocado_ca
    .groupby(["geography", "type"])["average_price"]
    .agg(["mean", "std", "count"])
    .reset_index())

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, facet_wrap, labs, theme_bw, theme, scale_fill_manual, scale_y_continuous, element_text

# Order the bars
size_order = ["xl_avocados", "large_avocados", "small_avocados"]
ca_long_prop["size"] = pd.Categorical(ca_long_prop["size"], categories=size_order, ordered=True)

# Plot
(ggplot(ca_long_prop, aes(x="geography", y="proportion", fill="size"))
    + geom_bar(stat="identity", position="stack")
    + facet_wrap("~ type")
    + scale_fill_manual(
        values={
            "small_avocados": "darkorange",
            "large_avocados": "mediumseagreen",
            "xl_avocados": "slateblue"},
        name="Avocado Size",
        labels=["X-Large", "Large", "Small"])

        limits=(0, 1),
        breaks=[0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1],

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, facet_wrap,labs, theme_bw, theme, element_text

(ggplot(combined_data, aes(x="median_home_value", y="avg_price", color="geography"))
    + geom_point(size=2, alpha=0.7)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False, linetype="dashed", size=1)
    + labs(
        title="Relationship Between Home Prices and Avocado Prices",
        x="Median Home Value",
        y="Average Avocado Price",
        color="Region")
    + facet_wrap("~ type")
    + theme_bw()
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=20, hjust=1),
        figure_size=(9,6),
        legend_position="bottom"))

# The plot shows that cities with higher home prices tend to have higher average avocado prices, while more affordable areas such as Sacramento have lower prices for both.
# This suggests that avocado prices rise with overall cost of living, not that avocado spending causes high housing costs.
